McBurney et al. [30] defined context as the purpose of a method within the
code in which it exists. This context includes the dependencies of the method
and other methods that rely on it. In the context of design patterns, the term
referstothepurposeofaclasswithinthepattern—specifically,theroleitplays
in the class hierarchy, such as whether it acts as a subscriber or a publisher
(as in the Observer pattern), as well as the methods invoked within these
classes. Although McBurney’s approach focuses solely on the context of the
method, we argue that the context of the class is more critical when dealing
with design patterns. However, we capture both class and method contexts
in our summaries. Thus, we break down the context from the class level to
themethods.Thefollowingexample,takenfromtheRefactoringGuruGitHub
repository,2 illustrates the context.
public interface GUIFactory {
Button create Button ( ) ;
Checkbox create Checkbox ( ) ;
}
This code example illustrates that a GUI factory produces two types of
products,namelyButtonandCheckbox,asshownintheimplementationclass
below:
public class MacOSFactory implements GUIFactory {
@Override
public Button create Button ( ) {
return new MacOSButton ( ) ;
}
@Override
public Checkbox create Checkbox ( ) {
return new MacOSCheckbox ( ) ;
}
}
The code presented here illustrates how developers can create families of
related objects without specifying their concrete classes. The GUIFactory in-
terfaceestablishesacontractforproducingtwotypesofproducts:Buttonand
Checkbox. Concrete factories, such as MacOSFactory, implement this inter-
facetogenerateplatform-specificvariants(MacOSButtonandMacOSCheckbox).
